nRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59304"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with increasing confusion and lethargy over three days. She has metastatic neuroendocrine tumour diagnosed six months ago with liver metastases. Her medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, osteoarthritis, and chronic kidney disease. Her medications include oxycodone modified release 10 mg twice daily, paracetamol, amlodipine, metformin, insulin glargine, perindopril, and ondansetron as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears drowsy but rousable. Her pulse rate is 102/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She is clinically dehydrated with dry mucous membranes. Neurological examination reveals no focal deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECorrected calcium: 3.2 mmol/L (2.1-2.6)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 120 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003Cbr /\u003EeGFR: 42 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrea: 12.0 mmol/L (2.5-7.5)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlbumin: 32 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has received two litres of intravenous normal saline over the past four hours. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with no other abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Denosumab","Intravenous zoledronic acid","Glucocorticoids","Calcitonin","Oral calcium supplements"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic hypercalcaemia of malignancy, which is a common paraneoplastic complication of neuroendocrine tumours. The initial management involves volume expansion with intravenous fluids, which has already been initiated. The next step is to address the underlying mechanism of hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous zoledronic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Bisphosphonates are the first-line therapy for malignancy-associated hypercalcaemia after initial volume expansion. They work by inhibiting osteoclast-mediated bone resorption and typically lower calcium levels within 48-72 hours. Bisphosphonates can be given in renal impairment with adjusted dosages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcitonin\u003C/strong\u003E has a rapid but short-lived effect on calcium levels. While it can be used in severe cases, its effect is temporary, and it must always be given with bisphosphonates. It is not the preferred first-line agent, and evidence has shown time to normocalcaemia and clinical outcomes are similar when given in conjunction with bisphosphonates, vs monotherapy with bisphosphonates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral calcium supplements\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this situation as they would worsen the hypercalcaemia. These are used in the treatment of hypocalcaemia, not hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDenosumab\u003C/strong\u003E is a RANK ligand inhibitor that can be used in bisphosphonate-resistant hypercalcaemia or in patients with renal impairment. It is considered the agent of choice as a second-line treatment of patients with bisphosphonate-resistant malignancy hypercalcemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucocorticoids\u003C/strong\u003E are effective in treating hypercalcaemia due to certain conditions such as lymphoma or vitamin D toxicity, but they are not the first-line treatment for hypercalcaemia of solid tumours like neuroendocrine tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of malignancy-associated hypercalcaemia also requires ongoing monitoring of calcium levels, renal function, and addressing the underlying malignancy through appropriate oncological treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bisphosphonates are first-line therapy for malignancy-associated hypercalcaemia after initial volume expansion with IV fluids, with dose adjustment and monitoring in those with renal impairment.","Symptoms of hypercalcaemia include confusion, lethargy, constipation, and polyuria.","Corrected calcium \u003E3.0 mmol/L requires urgent treatment due to risk of cardiac arrhythmias and coma.","Denosumab is the agent of choice as a second-line treatment of patients with bisphosphonate-resistant malignancy hypercalcemia."],"references":["Almuradova E, Cicin I. Cancer-related hypercalcemia and potential treatments. Frontiers in Endocrinology. 2023 Mar 22;14:1039490. Available online at ; https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/endocrinology/articles/10.3389/fendo.2023.1039490/full","Chung C, Allen E, Umoru G. Paraneoplastic syndromes: A focus on pathophysiology and supportive care. American Journal of Health-System Pharmacy. 2022 Nov 15;79(22):1988-2000. Available online at ; https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Clement-Chung/publication/362451504_Paraneoplastic_syndromes_A_focus_on_pathophysiology_and_supportive_care/links/64740ab759d5ad5f9c82991a/Paraneoplastic-syndromes-A-focus-on-pathophysiology-and-supportive-care.pdf","Khan AA, Gurnani PK, Peksa GD, Whittier WL, DeMott JM. Bisphosphonate Versus Bisphosphonate and Calcitonin for the Treatment of Moderate to Severe Hypercalcemia of Malignancy. Annals of Pharmacotherapy. 2021;55(3):277-285. doi:10.1177/1060028020957048. Available online at ; https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/1060028020957048"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44715"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14652"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisi